  "final_answer": "## Il Messaggero's Coverage of Mussolini's Fall and the Badoglio Transition (July 25-27, 1943)\n\nIl Messaggero's coverage of this watershed moment reveals a dramatic editorial shift that occurred between July 25 and 27, 1943. Notably, the issue of July 26 is absent from the archive, creating a crucial gap in the immediate aftermath of Mussolini's removal.\n\nOn **July 25, 1943**, the newspaper showed no indication of the regime change. That day's edition continued normal fascist-era coverage, including references to \"Bruno Mussolini\" sporting events and routine war bulletins, suggesting the Gran Consiglio meeting of July 24 and its consequences were not yet public knowledge or had occurred too late for publication.\n\nThe transformation becomes starkly visible in the **July 27, 1943** edition, which provided comprehensive coverage of the transition. The front page featured multiple proclamations and announcements. A key article, \"L'ordine del giorno e la votazione del Gran Consiglio nella riunione del 24\" (1943-07-27_a006), revealed that the Gran Consiglio del Fascismo had met on July 24 for the first time since December 7, 1939, with Grandi presenting an order of the day that called for restoring \"all state functions\" and assigning responsibilities \"to the Crown, the Gran Consiglio, the Government, the Parliament, and the Corporations.\"\n\nThe editorial register shifted dramatically from fascist rhetoric to monarchist-military language. The headline \"La composizione del Governo Badoglio\" (1943-07-27_a000) announced \"Another day of enthusiastic demonstrations by the people acclaiming Italy, the Armed Forces, the King and the Marshal.\" The article \"Carattere del nuovo Governo\" (1943-07-27_a040) praised the new government's \"military character\" and emphasized that only \"decisive, strenuous military energy\" could resolve Italy's crisis.\n\nConspicuously, Mussolini's name virtually disappeared, replaced by celebrations of King Victor Emmanuel III and Marshal Badoglio. Articles described popular demonstrations with \"tricolor flags\" and photographs of \"the King and Badoglio\" (1943-07-27_a021). The appointment of Carmine Senise as Chief of Police was celebrated as a \"reintegration\" of \"an upright gentleman\" who embodied \"justice\" (1943-07-27_a040).\n\nGerman reactions, reported cautiously, attributed the change to \"Mussolini's state of health\" while emphasizing that \"the war continues\" (1943-07-27_a033). This marked Il Messaggero's abrupt pivot from fascist organ to monarchist mouthpiece, reflecting the regime's overnight transformation while maintaining continuity on the war effort.",
